If you own 10% of a business, and it made $1 million of profits this year, =
how much do you have to pay in taxes on that income?
In the US, there are two common answers to this question. One is that your =
income includes 10% of the business=E2=80=99s income, so you have $100,000 =
of income and pay, say, $37,000 of taxes on=C2=A0it (at the top federal inc=
ome tax rate of  37%). This is the normal way that, for instance, law firms=
 are taxed: A partner who owns a one-tenth share of the law firm counts 10%=
 of the firm=E2=80=99s income in her income, and pays taxes on it. It=E2=80=
=99s the normal way that   most hedge fund managers are taxed. More general=
ly, it=E2=80=99s the normal way that partnerships, limited partnerships, ma=
ny limited liability companies and a lot of corporations
  [1]
 are treated: Their income is treated as taxable income of their owners, wh=
o report their share of the income on their individual tax returns. They ar=
e called =E2=80=9Cpass-through entities,=E2=80=9D because their income is p=
assed through to their owners.
The other common answer is that your income=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0inclu=
de any of the business=E2=80=99s income. This is the normal way that=C2=A0l=
arge corporations are treated: If you own 10% of Meta Platforms Inc., you d=
on=E2=80=99t pay taxes on 10% of Meta=E2=80=99s income. You don=E2=80=99t p=
ay any taxes on Meta=E2=80=99s income, even if you are Mark Zuckerberg. Ins=
tead:
=09The corporation itself generally pays taxes on its income: It is treated=
 as its own separate tax entity, not a =E2=80=9Cpass-through,=E2=80=9D and =
has its own taxable income and pays its own taxes. These are corporate taxe=
s, which are generally at a lower rate than individual taxes; the current  =
federal corporate tax rate is 21%.=09If the corporation pays any cash divid=
ends, you pay taxes on the dividends you get, at a  capital gains tax rate =
of up to 20%.
  [2]

=09When you eventually=C2=A0sell=C2=A0your stock, you pay taxes on your gai=
ns (i.e. the difference between the price you sell for and the price you bo=
ught at), also at the  capital gains rate of up to 20%.
  [3]



Schematically, if you buy 10% of a corporation=C2=A0for $500,000 (i.e. the =
corporation is worth $5 million), and it makes $1 million of income this ye=
ar, then it pays $210,000 of income taxes, leaving $790,000 of income. If i=
t puts that income in the bank, then your stock is now worth $579,000 (i.e.=
 the value of the corporation is now $5.79 million, because of the cash), a=
nd if you sell it next year then you will have a $79,000 capital gain and p=
ay $15,800 of taxes.=C2=A0But if you don=E2=80=99t sell it you won=E2=80=99=
t.
There are advantages and disadvantages to this, for you. The disadvantage i=
s that the income is taxed twice, once (at 21%) when the corporation earns =
it and once (at up to 20%) when you sell the stock (or get a dividend); if =
the income was passed through you=E2=80=99d just pay your own tax rate (up =
to 37%) on it. The main advantage is that you don=E2=80=99t have to pay you=
r share of the taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0the capital gains tax =E2=80=94=C2=A0un=
til you want to. As long as you don=E2=80=99t sell the stock (and it doesn=
=E2=80=99t pay dividends), you don=E2=80=99t have to write any checks to th=
e Internal Revenue Service. You can let the money compound in the corporati=
on without paying taxes.
The real advantage is when you can do this forever. For instance:
=09You buy a stock, its value keeps going up, you don=E2=80=99t sell it and=
 you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes.=09If you need cash, you go to your broker and=
 take out a loan, secured by=C2=A0the value of the stock.=09If the stock ke=
eps going up, you never pay back the loan, and you can borrow more money if=
 you want.
  [4]

=09Eventually you die, your heirs get the stock, and they=C2=A0don=E2=80=99=
t pay taxes=C2=A0on your gains. (This is called the =E2=80=9Cbasis step-up=
=E2=80=9D: When you inherit stock, the IRS pretends that you paid market va=
lue for it, so you don=E2=80=99t have to pay taxes on the previous gains.)

This is sometimes called the =E2=80=9Cbuy, borrow, die=E2=80=9D tax strateg=
y: You get to benefit from the income of the business without ever paying t=
axes on it. I mean, not entirely =E2=80=94=C2=A0the corporation itself does=
 generally pay corporate income taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0but partially. And=C2=
=A0if the business does=C2=A0not=C2=A0pay US corporate income taxes =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0for instance because it is a foreign corporation with a different =
tax regime =E2=80=94=C2=A0then things could be even better, for you, as a t=
ax matter.
That is a rough overview of how US business income taxation works, though=
=C2=A0oh boy is it not legal advice. These are, roughly speaking, the rules=
. The US tax code treats some sorts of business income the first way (pass-=
through taxation), and it treats some sorts of business income the second w=
ay (two-layer corporate taxation), but for a whole lot of businesses  it=C2=
=A0lets them choose which way they would like to be taxed. If you start a l=
imited liability company you can tell the IRS whether you=E2=80=99d like to=
 pay pass-through taxes or corporate taxes, and the IRS will let you do whi=
chever=C2=A0you want. (The most important exception is that widely held cor=
porations=C2=A0normally have to pay corporate taxes and can=E2=80=99t choos=
e to be pass-throughs.)
People sometimes complain about this. Sometimes they complain about corpora=
te taxation, saying that it is =E2=80=9Cdouble taxation=E2=80=9D of the sam=
e income and thus unfair. So they argue that corporate tax rates, or capita=
l gains rates, or both, should be lower, or zero.
But you could have a more philosophical complaint about=C2=A0pass-through=
=C2=A0taxation. You could say that it=C2=A0is unfair, because you have to p=
ay taxes on income you haven=E2=80=99t necessarily received. If you are a p=
artner in a law firm, and you own 10%, and the firm makes $1 million, and t=
he firm decides to keep the money in its firm checking account and not dist=
ribute any of it to you, then you have to pay taxes on $100,000 of income t=
hat you have not actually received. Seems a little unfair. (In practice man=
y partnerships  make tax distributions to make sure that all their partners=
 have enough cash to pay the tax bills on the firm=E2=80=99s income, but th=
at=E2=80=99s not a law of nature and the partnership might decide not to se=
nd out any money.)
This is a philosophical complaint but you could also make it a constitution=
al complaint. The  Sixteenth Amendment to the US Constitution says that =E2=
=80=9Cthe Congress shall have power to lay and collect taxes on incomes, fr=
om whatever source derived,=E2=80=9D and you could say, well, no, this isn=
=E2=80=99t income. You are paying tax on $100,000 of the business=E2=80=99s=
 money, but you never got that money, so it isn=E2=80=99t income to you, so=
 Congress can=E2=80=99t tax it.
  [5]

In practice you do not see a lot of law firm partners arguing that it is un=
constitutional to tax them on their firms=E2=80=99 income, in part for prac=
tical reasons (they usually=C2=A0do=C2=A0get the money) and in part for leg=
al reasons (it=E2=80=99s a silly argument).
However! There are two reasons that this sort of question has become more i=
nteresting lately. One is that there is increasing interest, in the US gove=
rnment, in some sort of =E2=80=9Cbillionaire tax.=E2=80=9D Exactly what thi=
s means is debatable, but broadly speaking the Constitution allows income t=
axes but not wealth taxes, so a tax like =E2=80=9Cbillionaires have to pay =
1% of their wealth each year=E2=80=9D would have problems. So instead,   Bl=
oomberg reports:
[President Joe] Biden rejected an outright wealth tax as advocated by [Sena=
tor Elizabeth] Warren during the 2020 campaign but has since embraced a sca=
led-back version. His most recent budget would require taxpayers worth more=
 than $100 million to pay a minimum of 25% on their capital gains each year=
, whether they sold assets for a profit or continue to hold them. Biden tou=
ted it at this year=E2=80=99s State of the Union Address as a =E2=80=9Cbill=
ionaire minimum tax.=E2=80=9D
One way to think about this is that the =E2=80=9Cbillionaire minimum tax=E2=
=80=9D is sort of=C2=A0a way to apply the pass-through tax principles to co=
rporate shares.
  [6]
 If you own, say,  20% of Tesla Inc., you don=E2=80=99t pay any taxes on it=
s income (though it pays corporate taxes), and you don=E2=80=99t pay any ta=
xes on the increasing value of your shares until you   sell them. And so if=
 you wanted to you could   borrow money against those shares, live lavishly=
, =E2=80=9Cbuy borrow die" and=C2=A0never pay taxes. An ordinary worker who=
 makes $100,000 per year pays something like  $17,000 of taxes=C2=A0on that=
 $100,000 increase in her wealth. A shareholder whose shares go up by $100 =
million in a year, but who doesn=E2=80=99t sell, pays no tax on that increa=
se in her wealth.=C2=A0=C2=A0The =E2=80=9Cbillionaire minimum tax=E2=80=9D =
would make her pay 25%.
But the relevant legal question is: Is that=C2=A0income? In some rough econ=
omic sense, if your shares go up by $100 million, you are $100 million weal=
thier, and that seems like income. But it=E2=80=99s not quite the same thin=
g as getting a $100 million check in the mail. Historically, unrealized cap=
ital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0increases in value of assets that you don=E2=80=
=99t sell =E2=80=94 have not been taxed as income in the US, and it would b=
e jarring =E2=80=94=C2=A0and possibly unconstitutional =E2=80=94=C2=A0to st=
art.
The other reason that this stuff is getting more attention=C2=A0is a fairly=
 minor one involving a law that Congress passed in 2017 to change how forei=
gn corporate income is taxed. The  Wall Street Journal explains:

Before then, U.S. companies paid foreign taxes on foreign profits but could=
 defer any U.S. taxes until they brought earnings back home. Republicans sw=
itched to a system with a minimum annual U.S. tax on foreign profits and ta=
x-free repatriation.
In that transition, to deal with 30 years of profits companies had accumula=
ted overseas that hadn=E2=80=99t faced U.S. taxation, Congress imposed a on=
e-time levy.=C2=A0
The bulk of the estimated $338 billion in revenue that change generated is =
being paid by large companies such as Apple, Alphabet and Microsoft. But th=
e tax also applied to some individuals, including those who owned more than=
 10% of a foreign corporation. =C2=A0

If you=E2=80=99re Apple Inc. and you earned $100 billion from your overseas=
 subsidiaries over 30 years=C2=A0and kept the money in those subsidiaries, =
the IRS sent you a big one-time bill for taxes on those profits in 2018, an=
d you paid it. (Presumably you wired some money from those overseas subsidi=
aries into your US bank accounts to pay the taxes.) But if you=E2=80=99re j=
ust some individual who owns 10% of a foreign company that made money over =
30 years, the IRS sent you a one-time bill for taxes on those profits, and =
you might have trouble paying it. The foreign company might not have sent y=
ou any of the money, and as a 10% holder located thousands of miles away fr=
om the company, you probably can=E2=80=99t make it send you the money. So i=
t is arguably a bit rough to make you pay taxes on it.
  [7]

This is what happened to=C2=A0Charles and Kathleen Moore, who in the early =
2000s put $40,000 into a friend=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cbusiness to supply farme=
rs in India=E2=80=99s most impoverished regions with basic tools and equipm=
ent.=E2=80=9D
  [8]
=C2=A0That investment bought them about 13% of the stock in the friend=E2=
=80=99s Indian corporation, KisanKraft Machine Tools Private Limited. It di=
d well and=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwas profitable almost from the start=E2=80=9D; =E2=
=80=9CCharles visited India several times and was impressed with the differ=
ence that KisanKraft was making in the lives of India=E2=80=99s rural poor,=
=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cthe Moores never received any distributions, dividen=
ds, or other payments from KisanKraft,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cas minority sh=
areholders without any role in KisanKraft=E2=80=99s management, they had no=
 ability to force the company to issue a dividend.=E2=80=9D
And in 2018 they were hit with a $14,729 tax bill on $135,512 of historical=
 KisanKraft earnings. They paid, sued for a refund, lost in lower courts, a=
nd appealed to the US Supreme Court, which will hear their arguments tomorr=
ow. They argue that this isn=E2=80=99t income to them, so they shouldn=E2=
=80=99t have to pay taxes. The argument is that an income tax has to be bas=
ed on =E2=80=9Cincome they had realized,=E2=80=9D that is, money that they =
actually got, not just on their ownership of property. Here is  their brief=
.
Here is the  government=E2=80=99s brief, which I find more convincing. Amon=
g other things it points out that this stuff happens all the time: Partners=
 (and limited liability company members, and S corporation shareholders) pa=
y taxes on their businesses=E2=80=99 income, whether or not they actually g=
et it in cash. If the Supreme Court decides that that=E2=80=99s unconstitut=
ional, then=C2=A0most of the regime of=C2=A0US business taxation is unconst=
itutional.
  [9]
=C2=A0It also points out that there are lots of other cases of unrealized i=
ncome being taxed. For instance, original issue discount bonds: If a compan=
y sells a zero-coupon bond for $50, and it matures in five years and pays b=
ack $100, the buyer of the bond is treated as getting $10 a year of interes=
t income,
  [10]
=C2=A0even though she doesn=E2=80=99t actually get paid any interest until =
the end.
My sense is that nobody actually wants to declare pass-through taxation of =
LLCs unconstitutional. This case would not have made it to the Supreme Cour=
t a few years ago. But the =E2=80=9Cbillionaire minimum tax=E2=80=9D idea r=
aises the stakes: If Congress really might tax any increase=C2=A0in wealth,=
 whether or not it is realized,=C2=A0then that opens up a lot of new taxing=
 possibilities, which makes people nervous. But if Congress=C2=A0can=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0tax any unrealized=C2=A0increase in wealth, then that closes off =
a lot of taxes that already exist.

