<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you own 10% of a business, and it made $1 m=
illion of profits this year, how much do you have to pay in taxes on that i=
ncome?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the US, there are two common answers to thi=
s question. One is that your income includes 10% of the business=E2=80=99s =
income, so you have $100,000 of income and pay, say, $37,000 of taxes on=C2=
=A0it (at the top federal income tax rate of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly90YXhmb3VuZGF0aW9uLm9y=
Zy9kYXRhL2FsbC9mZWRlcmFsLzIwMjMtdGF4LWJyYWNrZXRzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B489ac638" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> 37%</a>). This is the normal way that, for instance, la=
w firms are taxed: A partner who owns a one-tenth share of the law firm cou=
nts 10% of the firm=E2=80=99s income in her income, and pays taxes on it. I=
t=E2=80=99s the normal way that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMzAvc2N1bHB0b3ItaXMtZnVsbC1vZi1jb25mbGljdHM_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMTIwNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMjA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBc937230e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  most hedge fund managers</a> are taxed. More ge=
nerally, it=E2=80=99s the normal way that partnerships, limited partnership=
s, many limited liability companies and a lot of corporations<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> are treated: Their income is treated as taxable income of their owners=
, who report their share of the income on their individual tax returns. The=
y are called =E2=80=9Cpass-through entities,=E2=80=9D because their income =
is passed through to their owners.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other common answer is that your income=C2=
=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>include any of the business=E2=80=99s inco=
me. This is the normal way that=C2=A0large corporations are treated: If you=
 own 10% of Meta Platforms Inc., you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes on 10% of Meta=
=E2=80=99s income. You don=E2=80=99t pay any taxes on Meta=E2=80=99s income=
, even if you are Mark Zuckerberg. Instead:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The corporation itself generally pays =
taxes on its income: It is treated as its own separate tax entity, not a =
=E2=80=9Cpass-through,=E2=80=9D and has its own taxable income and pays its=
 own taxes. These are corporate taxes, which are generally at a lower rate =
than individual taxes; the current <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly90YXhmb3VuZGF0aW9uLm9yZy9kYXRhL2=
FsbC9zdGF0ZS9jb21iaW5lZC1mZWRlcmFsLXN0YXRlLWNvcnBvcmF0ZS10YXgtcmF0ZXMtMjAyM=
i8jOn46dGV4dD1Db21iaW5lZCUyMEZlZGVyYWwlMjBhbmQlMjBTdGF0ZSUyMENvcnBvcmF0ZSUy=
MEluY29tZSUyMFRheCUyMFJhdGVzJTIwaW4lMjAyMDIyLC1TZXB0ZW1iZXIlMjAyNyUyQyUyMDI=
wMjImdGV4dD1Db3Jwb3JhdGlvbnMlMjBpbiUyMHRoZSUyMFVuaXRlZCUyMFN0YXRlcyxhdCUyMG=
ElMjAyMSUyMHBlcmNlbnQlMjByYXRlLg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa1fcaf98" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> federal corporate tax rate is 21%</a>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">If the corporation pays any cash dividends, you pay taxes on the div=
idends you get, at a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW52ZXN0b3BlZGlhLmNvbS90ZXJtcy9xL3F1YWxp=
ZmllZGRpdmlkZW5kLmFzcA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa847b348" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> capital =
gains tax rate of up to 20%</a>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When you eventually=C2=A0<em>sell=
=C2=A0</em>your stock, you pay taxes on your gains (i.e. the difference bet=
ween the price you sell for and the price you bought at), also at the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi90YXh0b3BpY3MvdGM0MDk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9774d981"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> capital gains rate of up to 20%</a>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schematically, if you buy 10% of a corporation=
=C2=A0for $500,000 (i.e. the corporation is worth $5 million), and it makes=
 $1 million of income this year, then it pays $210,000 of income taxes, lea=
ving $790,000 of income. If it puts that income in the bank, then your stoc=
k is now worth $579,000 (i.e. the value of the corporation is now $5.79 mil=
lion, because of the cash), and if you sell it next year then you will have=
 a $79,000 capital gain and pay $15,800 of taxes.=C2=A0But if you don=E2=80=
=99t sell it you won=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are advantages and disadvantages to this=
, for you. The disadvantage is that the income is taxed twice, once (at 21%=
) when the corporation earns it and once (at up to 20%) when you sell the s=
tock (or get a dividend); if the income was passed through you=E2=80=99d ju=
st pay your own tax rate (up to 37%) on it. The main advantage is that you =
don=E2=80=99t have to pay your share of the taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0the capita=
l gains tax =E2=80=94=C2=A0until you want to. As long as you don=E2=80=99t =
sell the stock (and it doesn=E2=80=99t pay dividends), you don=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to write any checks to the Internal Revenue Service. You can let the mon=
ey compound in the corporation without paying taxes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The real advantage is when you can do this for=
ever. For instance:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You buy a stock, its value keeps going=
 up, you don=E2=80=99t sell it and you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you need cash, you go to your broker and t=
ake out a loan, secured by=C2=A0the value of the stock.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the stock keeps going up, you never pay back the l=
oan, and you can borrow more money if you want.<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually you die, your heirs ge=
t the stock, and they=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t pay taxes=C2=A0on your gains</=
em>. (This is called the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly90YXhmb3VuZGF0aW9uLm9yZy90YXhlZHU=
vZ2xvc3Nhcnkvc3RlcC11cC1pbi1iYXNpcy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf9f3b248" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">basis step-up</a>=E2=80=9D: When you inherit stock, the IRS pretends t=
hat you paid market value for it, so you don=E2=80=99t have to pay taxes on=
 the previous gains.)</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is sometimes called the =E2=80=9C<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDctMjYvbW9uZXktc3R1=
ZmYtaXQtcy1lYXN5LXRvLWJvcnJvdy1tb25leS1pZi15b3UtaGF2ZS1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQ=
xMjA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlci=
Z1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBe0b5d611" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">buy, borrow, die</a>=E2=80=9D tax strategy: You get t=
o benefit from the income of the business without ever paying taxes on it. =
I mean, not entirely =E2=80=94=C2=A0the corporation itself does generally p=
ay corporate income taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0but partially. And=C2=A0if the bus=
iness does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>pay US corporate income taxes =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0for instance because it is a foreign corporation with a different tax=
 regime =E2=80=94=C2=A0then things could be even better, for you, as a tax =
matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a rough overview of how US business in=
come taxation works, though=C2=A0oh boy is it not legal advice. These are, =
roughly speaking, the rules. The US tax code treats some sorts of business =
income the first way (pass-through taxation), and it treats some sorts of b=
usiness income the second way (two-layer corporate taxation), but for a who=
le lot of businesses <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9wdWIvaW50X3ByYWN0aWNlX3VuaXRz=
L29yZV9jXzE5XzAyXzAxLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd39a7825" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> it=
=C2=A0lets them choose</a> which way they would like to be taxed. If you st=
art a limited liability company you can tell the IRS whether you=E2=80=99d =
like to pay pass-through taxes or corporate taxes, and the IRS will let you=
 do whichever=C2=A0you want. (The most important exception is that <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9idXNpbmVzc2VzL3NtYWxsLWJ1c2luZXNzZXMtc2VsZi1lbXBsb3llZC9z=
LWNvcnBvcmF0aW9ucw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d959168" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">widely held c=
orporations</a>=C2=A0normally have to pay corporate taxes and can=E2=80=99t=
 choose to be pass-throughs.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People sometimes complain about this. Sometime=
s they complain about corporate taxation, saying that it is =E2=80=9C<a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6=
Ly90YXhmb3VuZGF0aW9uLm9yZy9yZXNlYXJjaC9hbGwvZmVkZXJhbC9jYXBpdGFsLWdhaW5zLXR=
heGVzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1727cd41" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">double taxation</a>=E2=
=80=9D of the same income and thus unfair. So they argue that corporate tax=
 rates, or capital gains rates, or both, should be lower, or zero.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you could have a more philosophical compla=
int about=C2=A0<em>pass-through=C2=A0</em>taxation. You could say that it=
=C2=A0is unfair, because you have to pay taxes on income you haven=E2=80=99=
t necessarily received. If you are a partner in a law firm, and you own 10%=
, and the firm makes $1 million, and the firm decides to keep the money in =
its firm checking account and not distribute any of it to you, then you hav=
e to pay taxes on $100,000 of income that you have not actually received. S=
eems a little unfair. (In practice many partnerships <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly9mcm9zdGJyb3du=
dG9kZC5jb20vdGF4LWRpc3RyaWJ1dGlvbnMtZm9yLXBhc3MtdGhyb3VnaC1lbnRpdHktb3duZXJ=
zLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB64c4cdd8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> make tax distributions</a> =
to make sure that all their partners have enough cash to pay the tax bills =
on the firm=E2=80=99s income, but that=E2=80=99s not a law of nature and th=
e partnership might decide not to send out any money.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a philosophical complaint but you coul=
d also make it a constitutional complaint. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb25zdGl0dXRpb24uY2=
9uZ3Jlc3MuZ292L2NvbnN0aXR1dGlvbi9hbWVuZG1lbnQtMTY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
9d871ad9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> Sixteenth Amendment</a> to the US Constitution says that=
 =E2=80=9Cthe Congress shall have power to lay and collect taxes on incomes=
, from whatever source derived,=E2=80=9D and you could say, well, no, this =
isn=E2=80=99t income. You are paying tax on $100,000 of the business=E2=80=
=99s money, but you never got that money, so it isn=E2=80=99t income to you=
, so Congress can=E2=80=99t tax it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice you do not see a lot of law firm p=
artners arguing that it is unconstitutional to tax them on their firms=E2=
=80=99 income, in part for practical reasons (they usually=C2=A0<em>do=C2=
=A0</em>get the money) and in part for legal reasons (it=E2=80=99s a silly =
argument).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However! There are two reasons that this sort =
of question has become more interesting lately. One is that there is increa=
sing interest, in the US government, in some sort of =E2=80=9Cbillionaire t=
ax.=E2=80=9D Exactly what this means is debatable, but broadly speaking the=
 Constitution allows income taxes but not wealth taxes, so a tax like =E2=
=80=9Cbillionaires have to pay 1% of their wealth each year=E2=80=9D would =
have problems. So instead, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjMtMTItMDQvYmlkZW4tcy1iaWxsaW9uYWlyZS10YXgtcGxhbi1hdC1yaXNrLW92ZXItd=
HJ1bXAtZXJhLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtY2FzZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMDQmdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb7113f98" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  B=
loomberg reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[President Joe] Biden rejected an =
outright wealth tax as advocated by [Senator Elizabeth] Warren during the 2=
020 campaign but has since embraced a scaled-back version. His most recent =
budget would require taxpayers worth more than $100 million to pay a minimu=
m of 25% on their capital gains each year, whether they sold assets for a p=
rofit or continue to hold them. Biden touted it at this year=E2=80=99s Stat=
e of the Union Address as a =E2=80=9Cbillionaire minimum tax.=E2=80=9D</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about this is that the =E2=80=
=9Cbillionaire minimum tax=E2=80=9D is <em>sort of=C2=A0</em>a way to apply=
 the pass-through tax principles to corporate shares.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> If you own, say, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2F=
yL2RhdGEvMTMxODYwNS8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjMwOTQwNzUvZDQ1MTM0MmRkZWYxNGEuaHRtI3RvYz=
Q1MTM0Ml81OQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd3fde05e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 20% of Tesla Inc.<=
/a>, you don=E2=80=99t pay any taxes on its income (though it pays corporat=
e taxes), and you don=E2=80=99t pay any taxes on the increasing value of yo=
ur shares until you <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjEtMTEtMTEvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXNvbGQtc29tZS10ZXNsYS1zdG9jay1rdnY3NGtjZT9jbXBp=
ZD1CQkQxMjA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2x=
ldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB439e879c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  sell them</a>. And so if you wanted to you =
could <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287=
407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMDYvdGV=
zbGEtYWx0ZXJzLXNoYXJlLXBsZWRnZS1wb2xpY3ktd2l0aC1jYXAtb24tZWxvbi1tdXNrLWJvcn=
Jvd2luZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb=
3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB39360928" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  borrow money against those sha=
res</a>, live lavishly, =E2=80=9Cbuy borrow die" and=C2=A0never pay taxes. =
An ordinary worker who makes $100,000 per year pays something like <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZmlkZWxpdHkuY29tL3RheC1pbmZvcm1hdGlvbi90YXgtYnJhY2tldHM/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB05e686eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> $17,000 of taxes</a>=C2=A0on that $100,000 =
increase in her wealth. A shareholder whose shares go up by $100 million in=
 a year, but who doesn=E2=80=99t sell, pays no tax on that increase in her =
wealth.=C2=A0=C2=A0The =E2=80=9Cbillionaire minimum tax=E2=80=9D would make=
 her pay 25%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the relevant legal question is: Is that=C2=
=A0<em>income</em>? In some rough economic sense, if your shares go up by $=
100 million, you are $100 million wealthier, and that seems like income. Bu=
t it=E2=80=99s not quite the same thing as getting a $100 million check in =
the mail. Historically, unrealized capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0increases i=
n value of assets that you don=E2=80=99t sell =E2=80=94 have not been taxed=
 as income in the US, and it would be jarring =E2=80=94=C2=A0and possibly u=
nconstitutional =E2=80=94=C2=A0to start.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other reason that this stuff is getting mo=
re attention=C2=A0is a fairly minor one involving a law that Congress passe=
d in 2017 to change how foreign corporate income is taxed. The <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cud3NqLmNvbS91cy1uZXdzL2xhdy9vbmUtc3VwcmVtZS1jb3VydC1jYXNlLWNvdWxkLW1lc3Mtd=
XAtY2h1bmtzLW9mLXRoZS10YXgtY29kZS02ODBhOWJhNj9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M1/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBe1ba780d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal explains</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before then, U.S. companies paid foreign taxes=
 on foreign profits but could defer any U.S. taxes until they brought earni=
ngs back home. Republicans switched to a system with a minimum annual U.S. =
tax on foreign profits and tax-free repatriation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In that transition, to deal with 30 years of p=
rofits companies had accumulated overseas that hadn=E2=80=99t faced U.S. ta=
xation, Congress imposed a one-time levy.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bulk of the estimated $338 billion in reve=
nue that change generated is being paid by large companies such as Apple, A=
lphabet and Microsoft. But the tax also applied to some individuals, includ=
ing those who owned more than 10% of a foreign corporation. =C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you=E2=80=99re Apple Inc. and you earned $1=
00 billion from your overseas subsidiaries over 30 years=C2=A0and kept the =
money in those subsidiaries, the IRS sent you a big one-time bill for taxes=
 on those profits in 2018, and you paid it. (Presumably you wired some mone=
y from those overseas subsidiaries into your US bank accounts to pay the ta=
xes.) But if you=E2=80=99re just some individual who owns 10% of a foreign =
company that made money over 30 years, the IRS sent you a one-time bill for=
 taxes on those profits, and you might have trouble paying it. The foreign =
company might not have sent you any of the money, and as a 10% holder locat=
ed thousands of miles away from the company, you probably can=E2=80=99t mak=
e it send you the money. So it is arguably a bit rough to make you pay taxe=
s on it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is what happened to=C2=A0Charles and Kath=
leen Moore, who in the early 2000s put $40,000 into a friend=E2=80=99s =E2=
=80=9Cbusiness to supply farmers in India=E2=80=99s most impoverished regio=
ns with basic tools and equipment.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That investment bought them about 13% of the stock in the friend=
=E2=80=99s Indian corporation, KisanKraft Machine Tools Private Limited. It=
 did well and=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwas profitable almost from the start=E2=80=9D; =
=E2=80=9CCharles visited India several times and was impressed with the dif=
ference that KisanKraft was making in the lives of India=E2=80=99s rural po=
or,=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cthe Moores never received any distributions, divi=
dends, or other payments from KisanKraft,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cas minority=
 shareholders without any role in KisanKraft=E2=80=99s management, they had=
 no ability to force the company to issue a dividend.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in 2018 they were hit with a $14,729 tax b=
ill on $135,512 of historical KisanKraft earnings. They paid, sued for a re=
fund, lost in lower courts, and appealed to the US Supreme Court, which wil=
l hear their arguments tomorrow. They argue that this isn=E2=80=99t income =
to them, so they shouldn=E2=80=99t have to pay taxes. The argument is that =
an income tax has to be based on =E2=80=9Cincome they had realized,=E2=80=
=9D that is, money that they actually got, not just on their ownership of p=
roperty. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
3576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9Eb2NrZXRQREYvMjIvMjIt=
ODAwLzI3ODQ2NC8yMDIzMDgzMDEwMjUzNjIxN18yMi04MDAlMjBCcmllZiUyMGZvciUyMFBldGl=
0aW9uZXJzLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77f224da" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> their brief</a>=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdv=
di9Eb2NrZXRQREYvMjIvMjItODAwLzI4NTIwMC8yMDIzMTAxNjE5NTA0MTM5MF8yMi04MDBic1V=
uaXRlZCUyMFN0YXRlcy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB344e94a7" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> govern=
ment=E2=80=99s brief</a>, which I find more convincing. Among other things =
it points out that this stuff happens all the time: Partners (and limited l=
iability company members, and S corporation shareholders) pay taxes on thei=
r businesses=E2=80=99 income, whether or not they actually get it in cash. =
If the Supreme Court decides that that=E2=80=99s unconstitutional, then=C2=
=A0<em>most </em>of the regime of=C2=A0US business taxation is unconstituti=
onal.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It also points out that there are lots of other cases of unrealiz=
ed income being taxed. For instance, original issue discount bonds: If a co=
mpany sells a zero-coupon bond for $50, and it matures in five years and pa=
ys back $100, the buyer of the bond is treated as getting $10 a year of int=
erest income,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>=C2=A0even though she doesn=E2=80=99t actually get paid any interest un=
til the end.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My sense is that nobody actually wants to decl=
are pass-through taxation of LLCs unconstitutional. This case would not hav=
e made it to the Supreme Court a few years ago. But the =E2=80=9Cbillionair=
e minimum tax=E2=80=9D idea raises the stakes: If Congress really might tax=
 any increase=C2=A0in wealth, whether or not it is realized,=C2=A0then that=
 opens up a lot of new taxing possibilities, which makes people nervous. Bu=
t if Congress=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>tax any unrealized=C2=A0incr=
ease in wealth, then that closes off a lot of taxes that already exist.</p>
