</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDgtMTIvdGhlLTEwLWxhd3Mtb2YtaW5zaWRlci10cmFkaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDEyMDQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTIwNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB2f158284" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> Fifth Law of Insider Trading</a> is =E2=80=9Cdon=
=E2=80=99t do it by planting bombs at a company and shorting its stock,=E2=
=80=9D but I suppose there=E2=80=99s an argument the other way. My point wa=
s=C2=A0that if you are <em>fundamentally an insider trader</em>, getting in=
to terrorism is a bad career move: You are much more likely to get in much =
more trouble if you add some bombing to your white-collar crimes. But from =
the other perspective, if you are=C2=A0<em>fundamentally a terrorist</em>, =
I suppose it makes sense to get into insider trading? If you were going to =
blow up a company=E2=80=99s facilities <em>anyway</em>, for ideological rea=
sons, I can see why you=E2=80=99d also want to make money trading on it. Th=
ere are laws against insider trading, but they may not provide much <em>add=
itional</em> deterrence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway many, many readers sent me stories abou=
t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33576193.287407/=
aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQ2NTI=
wMjc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8095eb59" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this new paper</a>, by Rob=
ert Jackson and Joshua Mitts, suggesting that Hamas might have insider trad=
ed ahead of its October 7 attacks on Israel.=C2=A0Well, no, they suggest th=
at=C2=A0<em>someone=C2=A0</em>might have traded on advance knowledge of the=
 attacks, not necessarily Hamas:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Recent scholarship shows that info=
rmed traders increasingly disguise trades in economically linked securities=
 such as exchange-traded funds (ETFs). Linking that work to longstanding li=
terature on financial markets=E2=80=99 reactions to military conflict, we d=
ocument a significant spike in short selling in the principal Israeli-compa=
ny ETF days before the October 7 Hamas attack. The short selling that day f=
ar exceeded the short selling that occurred during numerous other periods o=
f crisis, including the recession following the financial crisis, the 2014 =
Israel-Gaza war, and the COVID-19 pandemic. Similarly, we identify increase=
s in short selling before the attack in dozens of Israeli companies traded =
in Tel Aviv. For one Israeli company alone, 4.43 million new shares sold sh=
ort over the September 14 to October 5 period yielded profits (or avoided l=
osses) of 3.2 billion NIS on that additional short selling. Although we see=
 no aggregate increase in shorting of Israeli companies on U.S. exchanges, =
we do identify a sharp and unusual increase, just before the attacks, in tr=
ading in risky short-dated options on these companies expiring just after t=
he attacks. We identify similar patterns in the Israeli ETF at times when i=
t was reported that Hamas was planning to execute a similar attack as in Oc=
tober. Our findings suggest that traders informed about the coming attacks =
profited from these tragic events, and consistent with prior literature we =
show that trading of this kind occurs in gaps in U.S. and international enf=
orcement of legal prohibitions on informed trading.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All in all this strikes me as inconclusive: Th=
ere was abnormal trading in the ETF, but the ETF is tiny; there was basical=
ly one day (Oct. 2, a week before the attacks) with $12 million or so of tr=
ades, and otherwise the ETF traded a few hundred thousand dollars=E2=80=99 =
worth per day in the two weeks before Oct. 7, <em>below=C2=A0</em>its usual=
 daily volume. =E2=80=9CWhile the magnitude of additional trading in the Is=
raeli ETF is abnormal, it is not large in absolute terms, likely owing to t=
he limited trading volume and liquidity in that ETF,=E2=80=9D they write. T=
hey place more emphasis on the trading on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, but=
=C2=A0here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3357=
6193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi5nbG9iZXMuY28uaWwvZW4vYXJ0aWNsZS1odWdlLWVycm9ycy1=
pbi11cy1zdHVkeS1hYm91dC10YXNlLXNob3J0LXNlbGxlcnMtMTAwMTQ2NDA5OA/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB208c32bb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">a report</a>=C2=A0claiming that they overes=
timate that trading=C2=A0due to a mistake about quoting conventions. And th=
ere is some US=C2=A0option trading, where they say that =E2=80=9Cthe eviden=
ce we present is consistent with substantial block trades that occurred on =
October 2 rather than ordinary market-making activity.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have trouble imagining Hamas calling an opti=
ons market maker to do block trades. But I also don=E2=80=99t really unders=
tand why outside tippees would=C2=A0have advance knowledge of the attacks a=
nd do all their trading a week ahead of time: Wouldn=E2=80=99t a more ordin=
ary model involve information leaking out over time and leading to increase=
d trading in the days leading up to the event? But, anyway, there you go, s=
ome people apparently did make some money trading=C2=A0ahead of the October=
 7 attacks.</p>
