<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMzAvZmFrZS13ZXdvcmstcmVzY3Vlci13YXMtYW4taG91ci1sYXRl=
P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1=
uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTIwNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB4a710114" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked last week</a> about a guy who =
bought a bunch of short-dated out-of-the money call options (and stock) on =
WeWork Inc.=C2=A0and then allegedly put out a fake press release announcing=
 that he was going to buy=C2=A0WeWork at a premium. This naturally caused t=
he stock to go up, making his options and stock more valuable, except that =
due to formatting errors and other delays he didn=E2=80=99t get the press r=
elease out until 5:12 p.m. on a Friday, at which point his options had expi=
red,=C2=A0the market was closed and he didn=E2=80=99t make any money. WeWor=
k filed for bankruptcy that weekend and the stock didn=E2=80=99t reopen unt=
il Wednesday, at which point everyone knew the press release was fake.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Several readers emailed to point out that=C2=
=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/33576193.287407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cub3B0aW9uc2VkdWNhdGlvbi5vcmcvcmVmZXJ=
lbmNlbGlicmFyeS9mYXEvb3B0aW9ucy1leGVyY2lzZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB841671=
82" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">you have until 5:30 p.m.</a> on the expiration date to exercis=
e your options, so=C2=A0<em>in theory=C2=A0</em>the guy could have gotten t=
he press release out late, quickly exercised his options and sold the stock=
. Still, that would not=C2=A0really help: The stock went=C2=A0<em>up</em>, =
in after-hours trading, on his fake press release, but it barely got above =
the strike prices of some of his options, and that only later in the evenin=
g after the options expired. The trick with this thing is to actually move =
the stock price (and, more important, the options price) during trading hou=
rs, and then sell your options (rather than exercising them), and if you wa=
it until 5:12 most of the gamblers have gone home and it doesn=E2=80=99t wo=
rk.</p>
